<seg id="1">Joint report on the parallel audits of expenditure on the construction of the Prague - Dresden motorway Preliminary remark Modern, united Europe could only cope with the high volume of traffic between the partner states with considerable restrictions and quality losses without trans-European motorways.</seg>
<seg id="2">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="3">High-quality transport networks are essential for maintaining and increasing living standards in Europe.</seg>
<seg id="4">Ensuring fast, safe, reliable and economical passenger and freight traffic is an important task of the state.</seg>
<seg id="5">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="6">It requires a high degree of organizational, technical and financial efforts.</seg>
<seg id="7">When building and expanding a sustainable European transport infrastructure, it is often necessary to make difficult compromises with European and national political goals, such as protecting the environment.</seg>
<seg id="8">The construction of the transport infrastructure is complex, precisely because of the necessary environmental protection measures.</seg>
<seg id="9">When planning and awarding the construction of traffic routes, administrations can save considerable financial resources through careful action and decision-making and use them for other useful purposes.</seg>
<seg id="10">One of the tasks of state auditing authorities is to identify deficiencies that stand in the way of optimum economy, efficiency and effectiveness in the expenditure for the construction of traffic facilities.</seg>
<seg id="11">The auditing authorities should not only inform the administrations of the shortcomings identified, but also make suggestions for improvement for the benefit of the citizens and for the benefit of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="12">Summary</seg>
<seg id="13">In 2005 and 2006, the two Supreme Audit Institutions of the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic, the Federal Audit Office (BRH) and Nejvyšší kontrolní úřad (NKÚ), carried out parallel audits of the expenditure for the construction of the Prague - Dresden motorway (Autobahn D 8 in the Czech Republic and the A 17 motorway in the Federal Republic of Germany).</seg>
<seg id="14">The two highways are connected by a border bridge financed jointly by both countries.</seg>
<seg id="15">The cooperation with the NKÚ enabled the BRH to carry out an in-depth examination of the cost-effectiveness of the resources used in the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="16">As part of the cooperation with the BRH, the NKÚ received data from German bridges and tunnels for its own cost comparisons.</seg>
<seg id="17">In 2000 the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany signed a contract to build the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="18">In accordance with the planning progress, the completion date was finally set at the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">However, during the award procedure, the Road and Motorway Directorate of the Czech Republic (RMD) made mistakes that delayed the procedure and shortened the construction time available.</seg>
<seg id="20">The contract with the contractor was therefore concluded later than planned.</seg>
<seg id="21">The contractor assured the accelerated construction of the bridge until the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="22">However, the RMD had to accept considerable additional costs for this.</seg>
<seg id="23">As part of the joint audit activity, the prices of motorway bridges on the D 8 and A 17 were compared. The benchmark for the price comparison of the bridges was the size of the bridge area.</seg>
<seg id="24">A price analysis using statistical methods identified bridges with high costs per square meter.</seg>
<seg id="25">The analysis showed that the border bridge under the large bridges with lengths of over 100 m was the most expensive.</seg>
<seg id="26">This was also due to the price increase resulting from the delays in the award.</seg>
<seg id="27">The comparison of the prices for the tunnel structures showed that the prices of the tunnels in the course of the D 8 are considerably higher than the prices of comparable tunnels in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="28">BRH and NKÚ can rely on a data collection of bridge and tunnel prices for future checks of the cost-effectiveness of spending on transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="29">Both auditors recommend standardizing bridge constructions and executing steel composite and special constructions only where prestressed concrete constructions are inappropriate.</seg>
<seg id="30">The course of the exam was characterized by teamwork and an open approach.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the parallel examination, the examiners from both sides exchanged their specialist knowledge and skills.</seg>
<seg id="32">introduction</seg>
<seg id="33">The subject of this report is the parallel examination of expenditure on the construction of the motorway from Dresden to Prague (D 8 in the Czech Republic and A 17 in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="34">The focus of the examination was on economy, economy and effectiveness of the use of funds.</seg>
<seg id="35">The BRH in Germany and the NKÚ in the Czech Republic conducted the parallel tests</seg>
<seg id="36">in 2005 and 2006.</seg>
<seg id="37">The NKÚ checked the economy, efficiency and effectiveness of the expenditure for the border section 0807 of the D 8 motorway in the amount of approx. CZK 20 billion gross (around € 690 million).</seg>
<seg id="38">Of this amount, € 64 million will be made available from EU structural funds (ISPA).</seg>
<seg id="39">Regardless of the parallel tests with the NKÚ, the BRH had already checked the planning and construction of the A 17 motorway from 2003 to 2005.</seg>
<seg id="40">Of the financial volume for the construction of all three sections of the A 17 of approx. € 670 million, € 277 million will be co-financed from European funds (ERDF).</seg>
<seg id="41">The Prague - Dresden motorway is part of the Pan-European Transport Corridor IV Dresden - Central and Southeast Europe - Istanbul.</seg>
<seg id="42">The D 8 runs from Prague via Usti nad Labem to the Czech / German border,</seg>
<seg id="43">the A 17 from the border to Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="44">At the time of the inspection, sections of the motorway close to the border were under construction.</seg>
<seg id="45">Both sections were opened to traffic on December 21, 2006.</seg>
<seg id="46">While the motorway on the German side to Dresden is thus completed, the D 8 on the Czech side remains incomplete, since section 0805 over a length of 16.4 km between Rehlovice and Lovosice is still in the planning phase.</seg>
<seg id="47">The crossing of a landscape protection area in the Bohemian Uplands is planned here.</seg>
<seg id="48">According to Czech forecasts from 2001, the traffic volume in 2008 in the section 0807 of the D8 motorway near the border will be 22,940 vehicles per day.</seg>
<seg id="49">German forecasts estimate the traffic volume on the A 17 at the Czech border in 2010 at approx. 25,000 vehicles a day.</seg>
<seg id="50">In 2000, the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic signed a contract to merge the German A 17 motorway and the Czech D 8 motorway at the common state border by building a border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="51">Since both countries are involved in the construction of this bridge, this individual construction measure was an important aspect of the parallel audits of both audit offices.</seg>
<seg id="52">Cooperation between BRH and NKÚ</seg>
<seg id="53">From mid-2005, the two audit offices began to consider working together to examine the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway.</seg>
<seg id="54">Both sides had important reasons for this cooperation:</seg>
<seg id="55">1.</seg>
<seg id="56">Germany partially finances the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="57">Planning and construction are the responsibility of the Czech road construction administration.</seg>
<seg id="58">There was no way for the BRH to examine this construction project itself.</seg>
<seg id="59">2nd</seg>
<seg id="60">The NKÚ had no comparative data to assess whether the funds were used sparingly in view of the total construction costs of the bridges and tunnels on the D 8.</seg>
<seg id="61">3rd</seg>
<seg id="62">The NKÚ also had to check the effectiveness of the expenditure. For this purpose, the essential technical parameters of the bridges and tunnels should be examined, which should ensure the same quality of use on both sides of the border.</seg>
<seg id="63">After preliminary negotiations, the Presidents of the two Court of Auditors signed an agreement on January 4, 2006 to coordinate the audits of the Prague - Dresden motorway.</seg>
<seg id="64">The auditors of the two audit offices met approximately every six to eight weeks in the course of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="65">They dealt with current problems and tasks. They developed a uniform methodology for checking the bridge and tunnel prices, exchanged test results for the construction of the border bridge and prepared joint reports.</seg>
<seg id="66">The constant exchange of information was essential to the collaboration.</seg>
<seg id="67">While the BRH was primarily concerned with the comparison of the technical parameters of bridges and tunnels and the award procedure, the NKÚ mainly worked out the methodology for the analysis of the bridge and tunnel prices.</seg>
<seg id="68">In Germany and the Czech Republic, the legal basis for financial control differs, and with it the way in which the two audit offices complete their audits.</seg>
<seg id="69">For this reason, both authorities developed separate national reports on their test results.</seg>
<seg id="70">This report takes into account the results of the two parallel tests.</seg>
<seg id="71">The collaboration ends with the signing of a final communiqué in the first half of 2007.</seg>
<seg id="72">Construction of the border bridge</seg>
<seg id="73">In the 2000 contract, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany agreed to complete the border bridge in 2005 if possible.</seg>
<seg id="74">Later they agreed to postpone the appointment until the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="75">The RMD acted as the client for the construction project.</seg>
<seg id="76">Germany is financing 42.13% of the bridge construction.</seg>
<seg id="77">Initially, the RMD provided a prestressed concrete structure for the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="78">In 1999, however, the RMD agreed with its German partner on the construction of a steel composite structure.</seg>
<seg id="79">They justified this decision with the possible reduction in the number of pillar pairs from seven to five and the associated ecological benefits for the valley.</seg>
