<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the results of the parallel audit of sales tax administration in the Czech Republic and Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Foreword</seg>
<seg id="3">The Lima Declaration, adopted in 1977, emphasizes that the SAIs are empowered to audit all public finances.</seg>
<seg id="4">The declaration requires that the SAIs be empowered to review tax collection as widely as possible.</seg>
<seg id="5">The Organization of European Supreme Audit Institutions (EUROSAI) considers taxes to be an important part of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="6">The thematic focus of the VI. The EUROSAI Congress, which took place in Bonn in 2005, was the audit of public revenue by the audit offices.</seg>
<seg id="7">One of the most important steps on the way to optimizing the audit activity of an audit office is to develop a special strategy for auditing public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="8">This is especially true for taxes as the largest source of public revenue with a high risk of default.</seg>
<seg id="9">As national economies are increasingly interconnected and interdependent, a situation may arise in which national audit offices can only perform their audit work in cooperation with the audit offices of other countries.</seg>
<seg id="10">As an example, consider international fraud that can lead to significant revenue losses in many countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">Cooperation between authorities is required to combat such crimes.</seg>
<seg id="12">Auditors who audit in this area must be willing to work closely together.</seg>
<seg id="13">VI. EUROSAI Congress in Bonn. This audit was carried out in cooperation between the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the German Federal Court of Auditors.</seg>
<seg id="14">In the course of thorough preparation, the participating auditors first had to familiarize themselves with the legal framework and procedures for sales tax administration in the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="15">Based on the evaluation of the available information, we made the selection of the examination subjects for the examination planning.</seg>
<seg id="16">Achieving the ef ﬁ cient and effective management of sales tax has been a longstanding problem and individual states (particularly the EC Member States) are looking for solutions to improve the system, simplify the collection of sales tax and create greater transparency in this area.</seg>
<seg id="17">We are convinced that the results of our audit will not only help to improve the work of the financial administration, but may also form the basis for a proposal for an improved system for the international exchange of information.</seg>
<seg id="18">Report on the results of the parallel audit of sales tax administration in the Czech Republic and Germany</seg>
<seg id="19">introduction</seg>
<seg id="20">Case number: CZ) 06/27 (DE) VIII 2 - 2005 - 1215</seg>
<seg id="21">Subject of examination:</seg>
<seg id="22">(CZ) Sales tax administration after the Czech Republic joined the European Union</seg>
<seg id="23">(DE) Audit on administrative cooperation in the field of VAT in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and 1925/2004</seg>
<seg id="24">the commission's objective:</seg>
<seg id="25">(CZ) The aim of the audit in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedures used by the tax authorities in the area of ​​sales tax after the integration of the Czech Republic into the common internal market of the European Community (hereinafter "EC") with the free movement of goods and services and the Use of MIAS1, in particular the control of the use of the VAT exemption for intra-Community deliveries.</seg>
<seg id="26">(DE) The aim of the examination was to examine the system of intra-Community sales tax control with a focus on administrative assistance in the area of ​​sales tax in accordance with the above-mentioned regulations.</seg>
<seg id="27">As a result of the test, weak points should be identified and recommendations for their elimination should be made.</seg>
<seg id="28">Value Added Tax Information Exchange System The audits were carried out jointly by the Court of Audit of the Czech Republic ("NKÚ") and the Federal Audit Office ("BRH") of the Federal Republic of Germany on the basis of an agreement concluded on June 8, 2006.</seg>
<seg id="29">The focus of the cooperation was the review of selected business transactions between entrepreneurs from the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany, the exploitation of information obtained through international administrative assistance between the financial administrations and the comparison of the VAT administration systems in the two countries.</seg>
<seg id="30">A joint final report on the results of the tests was drawn up in accordance with European Guideline No. 31 for the implementation of the INTOSAI test standards.</seg>
<seg id="31">The audited period covered the period from May 1, 2004 to December 31, 2005.</seg>
<seg id="32">Summary of results and evaluation of the parallel test</seg>
<seg id="33">The parallel audit of sales tax administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two audit offices.</seg>
<seg id="34">In addition to the focus on information exchange in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No. 1798/2003 and Commission 1925/2004, other closely related aspects were also examined, e.g. registration of taxpayers, tax returns and summary reports.</seg>
<seg id="35">The audit also covered the legal situation in the case of cross-border passenger transport by bus and the comparison of statistical data.</seg>
<seg id="36">When comparing the VAT administration systems in the two countries, differences were found in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="37">1) Registration for VAT purposes.</seg>
<seg id="38">While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic, among other things, the main criterion for registration is the exceeding of the turnover threshold laid down in the turnover tax law.</seg>
<seg id="39">In the Czech Republic, taxpayers receive only one tax identification number, which they also use for intra-Community sales.</seg>
<seg id="40">In Germany, the taxpayer receives a tax number that is only valid for domestic sales for VAT purposes.</seg>
