<seg id="581">Comparison and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="582">Although it is not possible in the present report to deal with the specific criteria of the RMS in the Czech and Germany, the NKÚ and the BRH have determined that each member state has developed its own RMS.</seg>
<seg id="583">Like the different approaches in the three German federal states mentioned above, the RMS of each European country has its particular strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="584">There is currently an exchange of experience between the financial authorities of the European Member States on new trends and new models of cross-border VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="585">Sales tax fraud - especially carousel fraud - has proven to be not a national but a European problem.</seg>
<seg id="586">The people involved in fraud coordinate their actions not only in one but in several Member States.</seg>
<seg id="587">A Member State alone cannot develop an effective RMS.</seg>
<seg id="588">Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in every EC member state. If this does not happen, fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS for their crimes.</seg>
<seg id="589">The tax shortfalls caused by VAT fraud across Europe do not necessarily affect the Member State in which the initiator is located.</seg>
<seg id="590">Any other Member State involved in the fraud can be affected.</seg>
