<p>
<seg id="1">Public procurement and prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint report by the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on their parallel audits</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction and overview</seg>
<seg id="4">The awarding of services by public authorities is of great importance for both the state and the economy.</seg>
<seg id="5">The state's task is to use public funds as economically and economically as possible and to ensure fair and regulated competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">In the European Union (EU), the award of services by contracting authorities is an important part of creating a single economic area.</seg>
<seg id="7">In order to be able to guarantee largely unrestricted competition even across borders, the contracting authorities must follow EU guidelines when awarding certain value limits (threshold values).</seg>
<seg id="8">For this purpose, the EU member states have to translate and apply the EU public procurement law into national law.</seg>
<seg id="9">This has already happened in both the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="10">Below the EU thresholds, it is up to the individual countries to regulate the awarding of public contracts themselves.</seg>
<seg id="11">The award of services is also an area at risk of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="12">Because of the fundamentally high potential for damage, the contracting authorities must therefore take appropriate measures to prevent and prevent corruption and inadmissible benefits when awarding their contracts.</seg>
<seg id="13">The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed in January 2011 to carry out parallel audits both for the award of construction work throughout the EU and for the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="14">The focus of the audits was the application of the EU public procurement law, which was implemented in national regulations, and the prevention of corruption when awarding construction services in building construction, road construction or transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="15">Awards below the EU thresholds were also taken into account with a view to preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="16">The audit results of both SAIs are summarized in this joint report.</seg>
<seg id="17">The report is also intended for international institutions such as B. to the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).</seg>
<seg id="18">Audit areas and audited bodies The evaluations of the Federal Audit Office on the listed topics are mainly based on cross-sectional audits, which he carried out in 2011/2012 at the building authorities responsible for the road construction and building construction of the federal government in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="19">He checked z. B. the construction of highways and large building projects.</seg>
<seg id="20">In addition, the Federal Audit Office used results from previous investigations.</seg>
<seg id="21">The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic based its evaluations on audit findings from 2008 to 2011. The tests included construction work in road construction, railroad construction, hydraulic engineering, building construction (hospitals, cultural buildings, university buildings, etc.) and other other construction areas in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="22">In Germany, the federal government's building authorities predominantly award public contracts.</seg>
<seg id="23">In the Czech Republic, the state building administration is responsible for the award of transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="24">In building construction, the awards are carried out decentrally by those who use state budget funds.</seg>
<seg id="25">Freelancers are also involved in sub-areas of the procurement process in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="26">When comparing the evaluations, differences in public procurement law and the market structure for construction services in both countries must be taken into account.</seg>
<seg id="27">Development of public procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="28">In Germany, the implementation of EU-wide procurement procedures is laid down in laws and regulations.</seg>
<seg id="29">Procurement procedures restricted to the national area are regulated by budget law and the administrative regulations based on it.</seg>
<seg id="30">For both EU-wide and national contracts, many additional individual regulations are specified by internal administrative provisions,</seg>
<seg id="31">such as the so-called "procurement handbooks" of the federal government, in which the legal requirements are supplemented or formulated in more detail in compliance with the procurement law.</seg>
<seg id="32">In the Czech Republic, the procurement procedure is governed exclusively by the Public Procurement Act and other statutory provisions that apply both to the area above and below the EU thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="33">Public procurement law was significantly amended in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="34">The new regulation increased transparency in the use of public funds, enabled more competition and limited the possibility of corruption in the award procedure.</seg>
<seg id="35">Fundamentals of public procurement law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="36">In both countries, the open procedure, the restricted procedure and the negotiated procedure are to be used in particular for EU-wide awards.</seg>
<seg id="37">In Germany, the measures below the EU threshold must use the national types of award (public tender, restricted tender, direct award), which largely correspond to the EU-wide types of award mentioned.</seg>
<seg id="38">Public procurement law in Germany is characterized by the principle of the priority of the open procedure (for EU-wide contracts) and the public tender (for national contracts).</seg>
<seg id="39">Any interested company can submit an offer for the open procedure and the public tender.</seg>
<seg id="40">Another key feature of German public procurement law is the promotion of medium-sized companies.</seg>
<seg id="41">The main purpose here is to divide an overall construction project into specialist and partial lots.</seg>
<seg id="42">The individual awarding of these lots should enable as many companies as possible to participate in the competition.</seg>
<seg id="43">Both of the aforementioned features of German public procurement law are proven instruments for achieving economic results.</seg>
<seg id="44">There are over 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="45">In the Czech Republic, EU-wide procurement procedures also apply to construction projects below the EU threshold.</seg>
<seg id="46">The simplified procedure is an exception to this, in which a less strict procedure may be used below the threshold values ​​and under certain conditions.</seg>
<seg id="47">In accordance with EU law, Czech public procurement law contains provisions that contracts should be concluded if competition is guaranteed and a favorable price is achieved.</seg>
<seg id="48">The current legal provisions in the Czech Republic give contracting authorities the choice between open and restricted procedures.</seg>
<seg id="49">There are over 85,000 construction companies in the Czech Republic, including around 1,900 companies with 20 or more employees.</seg>
<seg id="50">Construction volume of contracting authorities and proportions of types of award in both countries</seg>
<seg id="51">The total construction volume in Germany in 2011 was EUR 307 billion.</seg>
<seg id="52">Of this, EUR 45.5 billion was attributable to public construction (15%), which in addition to the federal building also includes the construction measures of the federal states and municipalities.</seg>
<seg id="53">The federal building volume in building construction and trunk road construction (excluding railroad construction and hydraulic engineering) amounted to 8.5 billion euros.</seg>
<seg id="54">The volume of orders for construction work in building construction and trunk road construction by the federal government in 2011 was distributed as follows: 80.7% open procedures and public tenders, 12.7% restricted and restricted tenders and 6.6% negotiated procedures and Direct awards.</seg>
<seg id="55">Of these, 33.2% were awarded across Europe.</seg>
<seg id="56">The volume of public works in the Czech Republic in 2011 was 4.7 billion euros, which was about 25% of the total volume of all works in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="57">In 2009 the volume was EUR 7.8 billion, which corresponded to 37% of the total construction volume.</seg>
<seg id="58">Breakdown by type of award for 2011: 65.1% open procedures 14.3% non-public procedures 9.5% negotiated procedures 8.4% simplified procedures for order volumes below the threshold 2.7% other procedures</seg>
<seg id="59">The data refer to all public contracts for deliveries, services and works that were awarded in 2011 by public procurement agencies.</seg>
<seg id="60">The above Data show that the parallel audits of both countries are aimed at a significant proportion of public procurement, that the prevention of corruption that has to be observed for all procurement is of great financial importance and that the open procedure and the public tender are of great importance when awarding contracts</seg>
<seg id="61">Summary of the results of the parallel tests</seg>
<seg id="62">The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) have carried out parallel audits in their countries for the EU-wide award of construction works and for the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="63">In this context, the working groups of both audit offices compared the corresponding legal bases and administrative requirements in the Czech Republic and Germany as well as the results of their parallel audits, which they carried out in particular in the areas of building construction and road construction.</seg>
<seg id="64">They essentially found:</seg>
<seg id="65">The EU guidelines for the awarding of works by public authorities have been implemented in national law in the Czech Republic as well as in Germany (Nos. 1 and 3.1).</seg>
<seg id="66">In addition to the EU requirements, the prevention regulations for corruption also serve the two countries' procurement regulations, some of which differ in terms of their focus and level of detail (No. 3.2).</seg>
<seg id="67">In both countries, an essential requirement for the tender documents is that they must contain all the information required for the correct preparation of the offer.</seg>
<seg id="68">The service descriptions must be neutral and must not have any restrictions restricting competition.</seg>
<seg id="69">In Germany, the tender documents largely met these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="70">In the Czech Republic, it is still a problem to determine the object of the order adequately.</seg>
<seg id="71">In Germany, construction work should be divided into lots where possible in order to promote competition.</seg>
<seg id="72">According to the findings of the BRH, this requirement has been largely implemented in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="73">In its tests, particularly in the area of ​​road construction, the NKÚ found that the awarding of extensive services without lots or with only very large lots could impair competition and lead to a restriction to only a few large companies.</seg>
<seg id="74">Narrowing the market potential can result in significant cost increases and pose the risk of price or other agreements.</seg>
<seg id="75">According to the provisions of both countries, the awarding authorities can, under certain conditions, in principle agree additional or modified services with the companies already commissioned, which prove to be necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (No. 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="76">The respective requirements for determining the type of award were largely followed in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="77">According to the regulations of the Czech Republic, contracting entities can choose between open and restricted procedures.</seg>
<seg id="78">In Germany, on the other hand, the legal and budgetary anchored priority of the open procedure for EU-wide awards or the public tender applies, which corresponds to the open procedure for national awards.</seg>
<seg id="79">This allows more companies to submit offers.</seg>
<seg id="80">This reduces the risk of corruption, complicates price fixing between bidders and leads to the most economical results.</seg>
<seg id="81">In the case of construction projects whose estimated total contract values ​​reached or exceeded the EU threshold, the audited building authorities generally awarded the construction work across Europe.</seg>
<seg id="82">The correct estimation of the expected contract value is an essential basis when choosing the right type of award.</seg>
<seg id="83">In Germany, cost databases are used to determine the costs of public buildings, especially in building construction,</seg>
<seg id="84">which are based on the evaluations of completed construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="85">A database is used in the road construction sector in the Czech Republic, but it is not yet an effective tool (No. 4.2).</seg>
<seg id="86">Preliminary information and notices must be published for construction work to be awarded across Europe. This is intended to strengthen competition by allowing interested companies to adjust to the intended awards at an early stage.</seg>
<seg id="87">The audited building authorities generally adhered to this requirement.</seg>
<seg id="88">In individual cases, incorrect information, incorrect use or a lack of controls may have an impact on competition (No. 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="89">The selection of applicants for participation in non-public procurement procedures is particularly vulnerable to manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="90">According to EU law, the number of invited applicants must be high enough to guarantee real competition.</seg>
<seg id="91">The selection criteria must be objective, must not discriminate and must be announced in advance.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition to the requirements of the EU, the contracting authorities in both countries should change the selection of applicants as often as possible among the companies to be invited.</seg>
<seg id="93">In order to counter the risk of manipulation, there are sometimes very detailed guidelines in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="94">The audited administrations did not take these requirements into account in some cases.</seg>
<seg id="95">In the Czech Republic, the decisions regarding the selection of applicants were not always understandable (No. 4.4).</seg>
<seg id="96">In both countries, in the interests of fair competition, it must be ensured during the bidding phase that the companies interested in submitting a bid receive the same information.</seg>
<seg id="97">Contact between these companies and each other and with freelancers who were involved in the preparation of the service description should be avoided as far as possible to avoid anti-competitive agreements.</seg>
<seg id="98">The corresponding regulations in Germany are more extensive than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="99">Some of the audited building authorities in Germany did not meet these requirements (No. 4.5).</seg>
<seg id="100">When opening offers in both countries, the principle of multiple eyes and the principle of transparency must be observed.</seg>
<seg id="101">The requirements for the labeling, documentation, safekeeping and confidentiality of the offers are intended to restrict the scope for manipulation and are particularly detailed in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="102">The tests in both countries showed only a few complaints (No. 4.6).</seg>
<seg id="103">Examination and evaluation of the offers are defined in both countries by requirements for the structure and process organization.</seg>
<seg id="104">The regulations in Germany are more comprehensive, but have not been observed consistently by the auditing authorities.</seg>
<seg id="105">For example, contracting authorities handed over offers to third parties for review without first reviewing the offers and adequately documenting abnormalities.</seg>
<seg id="106">As a result, the offers were insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulation (No. 4.7).</seg>
<seg id="107">At the conclusion of the EU-wide tendering process, the companies participating in the competition should be informed of the intended contract before the contract is awarded.</seg>
<seg id="108">This legal protection option also has a preventive function against corruptive behavior.</seg>
<seg id="109">The Czech Republic also provides for judicial review options for non-EU procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="110">Only in a few cases did the contracting authorities fail to meet the specified deadlines when placing orders, or the content differed from the bidder's offer (No. 4.8).</seg>
<seg id="111">The documentation of the procurement procedures was not always complete or comprehensible for the audited building authorities in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="112">In this respect, the EU-wide transparency requirement was not adequately implemented in the award notes of some procedures.</seg>
<seg id="113">Some of the shortcomings identified also reduced the anti-corruption function of the documentation.</seg>
<seg id="114">The contracting authorities of both countries largely fulfilled their reporting and reporting obligations (No. 4.9).</seg>
<seg id="115">Fundamentals of EU procurement law and corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="116">EU procurement law</seg>
<seg id="117">In order to guarantee unrestricted competition in the European Union with the free movement of services and goods, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union the procurement coordination as well as the remedies directive, which the member states had to transpose into national law.</seg>
<seg id="118">The general procurement principles of the European Union are, in particular, the principle of competition, the principle of equal treatment or the prohibition of discrimination, and the principle of transparency.</seg>
<seg id="119">In order to achieve these goals, the procurement coordination guidelines contain special regulations for EU-wide construction work for construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="120">To this end, their expected order amounts must currently reach or exceed 5,000,000 euros.</seg>
<seg id="121">The regulations concern in particular the content of the tender documents, the publication of certain information before, during and after the award, compliance with deadlines, etc. for the receipt of the offers, the documentation of the award procedure, the requirements that can be placed on the qualifications of the applicants and the legal remedies directive forms the basis for the legal protection of the applicants and bidders.</seg>
<seg id="122">In the event of possible violations of public procurement law, the companies concerned can have the decisions of the contracting authorities reviewed in review procedures.</seg>
<seg id="123">Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have implemented the European Union directives into national law.</seg>
<seg id="124">Corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="125">Importance of corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="126">There is no legal definition of the concept of corruption in either country.</seg>
<seg id="127">In general, corruption is the misuse of a trust relationship for private gain,</seg>
<seg id="128">the usually is initiated by the beneficiaries of these decisions.</seg>
<seg id="129">Corruption can hinder competition and result in significant economic damage.</seg>
<seg id="130">The global cost of corruption is estimated to be 5% of global economic output.</seg>
<seg id="131">For the area of ​​the European Union, the scope of these costs is estimated at 1%.</seg>
<seg id="132">In the case of contracting authorities, restrictive agreements or unfair behavior can jeopardize trust in the integrity and functionality of the administration.</seg>
<seg id="133">Preventing corruption is therefore one of the fundamental tasks of contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="134">In doing so, they have to check the structure and process organization of their administrations for areas that are particularly susceptible to corruption in order to take appropriate security measures against corruption.</seg>
<seg id="135">Preventive measures and effective controls can significantly reduce the susceptibility of decision-making processes to corruptive abuse.</seg>
<seg id="136">The awarding of public works is generally seen as a work area that is particularly susceptible to corruption.</seg>
<seg id="137">Corruption prevention measures</seg>
<seg id="138">In Germany, corruption - especially bribery and bribery as well as acceptance and approval of benefits - is subject to criminal and labor law.</seg>
<seg id="139">To prevent corruption, the Federal Government has issued guidelines and recommendations for preventing corruption in the Federal Administration. According to this, in addition to risk analysis, the following principles in particular must be observed for the procurement area: priority of public tenders and open procedures, multiple-eyes principle and transparency, basic separation of planning, awarding and billing, precise and complete documentation of the awarding procedures.</seg>
<seg id="140">In addition, other anti-corruption requirements have been incorporated into the procurement regulations.</seg>
<seg id="141">For example, the responsible federal ministry for awarding federal trunk roads introduced an electronically supported control system in 2011,</seg>
<seg id="142">with the allocation data - such as B. the estimated costs and the order amounts - as well as information on the freelancers involved are collected across the board and evaluated for any abnormalities.</seg>
<seg id="143">Corruption is also subject to criminal and labor law in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="144">The statutory requirements of transparency and equal treatment of bidders as well as the ban on all forms of discrimination form the most important basis for the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="145">For public procurement, the Czech government has defined anti-corruption measures in a strategy paper to combat corruption for the years 2011 to 2012 and updated them for the years 2013 to 2014.</seg>
<seg id="146">Some of the measures recommended therein have already been implemented in national procurement law and corresponding administrative regulations14.</seg>
<seg id="147">The new legislation essentially contains the following regulations: lowering the threshold values ​​for smaller orders, the contracting authority has to notify the contracting authorities beforehand, including the reasons for the invitation to tender, the ban on restricting the number of bidders in restricted procedures and thus eliminating the possibility to select bidders Lottery procedure, introduction of the obligation to publish the order documents and all annexes, introduction of the obligation to publish the actual price and the list of subcontractors.</seg>
<seg id="148">Test results for the individual phases of the award procedure</seg>
<seg id="149">Procurement documents</seg>
<seg id="150">Procurement documents The procurement documents must contain all the information that the bidders need for a proper bid preparation.</seg>
<seg id="151">In particular, the tender documents must enable an accurate calculation.</seg>
<seg id="152">The bidders must not be assigned any risks that they cannot calculate.</seg>
<seg id="153">The tender documents consist in particular of the service description and the contractual terms.</seg>
<seg id="154">In addition, they contain the requirements for proving the qualification (suitability) of the bidders as well as the criteria that are decisive for the selection of the most economical offer.</seg>
<seg id="155">EU law and anti-corruption requirements</seg>
<seg id="156">The requirements of EU law on the procurement documents are directed in particular at the technical specifications.</seg>
<seg id="157">These must be equally accessible to all bidders and should restrict competition as little as possible.</seg>
<seg id="158">The service description must always be product-neutral.</seg>
<seg id="159">For this reason, information on products or manufacturers as part of the service description is only permitted under strict conditions.</seg>
<seg id="160">Avoiding competition-restricting requirements in the tender documents is also a fundamental principle of corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="161">In addition, unclear or inaccurate information in the tender documents should be avoided, as they open up scope for speculation when creating the offers and for manipulation when evaluating them.</seg>
<seg id="162">Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law</seg>
<seg id="163">Same or similar regulations In both countries, the EU legal requirements for the technical specifications have been implemented in national law.</seg>
<seg id="164">The services are generally to be advertised in a product-neutral manner without specifications.</seg>
<seg id="165">In the service descriptions, the individual services must generally be broken down in detail into service units with the respective quantities.</seg>
<seg id="166">The prices are to be agreed on the basis of performance units (e.g. euros per m² or per piece).</seg>
<seg id="167">Services can only be defined by functional targets in exceptional cases.</seg>
<seg id="168">The service descriptions must in any case be complete and unambiguous.</seg>
<seg id="169">They have to contain exact quantities and may not include services for which it is not certain whether they are needed.</seg>
<seg id="170">Payments based on lump sums or time expenditure should be avoided if possible.</seg>
<seg id="171">These provisions are intended to prevent speculation and manipulation based on indefinite requirements in the tender documents.</seg>
<seg id="172">The service descriptions must enable bidders to prepare their offers safely and without extensive preparatory work.</seg>
<seg id="173">The call for tenders should only be made known when the tender documents have been completed.</seg>
<seg id="174">Regulations that differ from each other</seg>
<seg id="175">There is no obligation to tender construction works in lots in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="176">If it is possible according to the type of service to be contracted, the public contracting authorities can divide construction services into several lots.</seg>
<seg id="177">In Germany, construction work must be divided into lots, separated by quantity (partial lots) and / or by type or subject (specialist lots).</seg>
<seg id="178">This should enable medium-sized companies to participate in the competition, expand the number of possible providers and make price agreements more difficult.</seg>
<seg id="179">This type of award is generally considered the most economical.</seg>
<seg id="180">In the Czech Republic, evaluation criteria must be specified in both the EU-wide and the national procedures in the tender documents.</seg>
<seg id="181">This should make it completely and finally clear to the applicants according to which criteria their offers should be evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="182">In Germany, the specification of evaluation criteria in EU-wide notices, but at the latest in the tender documents, is only required for EU-wide procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="183">In the case of national procurement procedures, the evaluation criteria are only to be recorded in an administrative award note.</seg>
<seg id="184">Procurement documents drawn up by contracted freelancers in Germany must not contain any references to these offices or the planners or experts involved in the building construction and some road construction administrations in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="185">This is to prevent individual companies from gaining additional information or other inadmissible competitive advantages without knowing the client about contacting these freelancers.</seg>
<seg id="186">This is also the reason why freelancers may neither send tender documents nor display planning documents for inspection.</seg>
<seg id="187">The contact person for the company is the client alone.</seg>
<seg id="188">There is currently no regulation in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="189">Additional or changed services that prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (supplements) are almost always required for large construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="190">To a certain extent, the legal provisions in both countries allow supplements to be given to the company that has already been commissioned without having to carry out an award procedure with public announcement.</seg>
<seg id="191">According to EU regulations and German regulations, the remuneration for supplementary services may not exceed half of the main order.</seg>
<seg id="192">In addition, the additional services must not be separated from the main contract without significant disadvantages or must be absolutely necessary.</seg>
<seg id="193">In the Czech Republic there is a narrower limit of 20% for a corresponding award without public announcement.</seg>
<seg id="194">However, this may increase the risk of a delayed completion of the construction project or the need to involve an additional contractor in the construction work already underway.</seg>
<seg id="195">If supplementary services are also transferred to the company already commissioned, an arbitrary price increase for these services by the contractor is fundamentally not possible according to the regulations in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="196">When determining the remuneration for the additional services, the agreed prices and the basis for determining the price of the order already placed must rather be assumed.</seg>
<seg id="197">In addition to supplementary benefits, the scope of benefits may also be reduced.</seg>
<seg id="198">In the Czech Republic, small quantities cannot be offset against additional supplements.</seg>
<seg id="199">Essential test results</seg>
<seg id="200">BHR</seg>
<seg id="201">Technical specifications and product-neutral tender</seg>
<seg id="202">In individual cases, the service descriptions contained references to national technical approvals or standards that had already been replaced by Europe-wide standards.</seg>
<seg id="203">Some performance descriptions also contained product-related requirements - for example for graffiti protection, joint tapes or noise protection panels - without this being necessary.</seg>
<seg id="204">In some cases, performance requirements were described so precisely that only one product was considered.</seg>
<seg id="205">Service specifications broken down into partial services</seg>
<seg id="206">The BRH has not found any violations of the requirement in any of the audited procedures to generally advertise services in a list of services broken down into partial services.</seg>
<seg id="207">Completeness of the service descriptions</seg>
<seg id="208">In the majority of the procedures, the tender documents were completed before the start of the tenders.</seg>
<seg id="209">In some procedures, the tender documents had to be corrected during the offer phase, as positions or deadlines had changed in some cases.</seg>
<seg id="210">Occasionally, the specifications contained items where it was not clear whether they were needed.</seg>
<seg id="211">Almost half of a bill of quantities for demolition work consisted of such demand items.</seg>
<seg id="212">Lots and evaluation criteria</seg>
<seg id="213">For many contracts, there was no prescribed reason why the services, which were mainly advertised according to the unskilled, were not further divided into partial lots.</seg>
<seg id="214">There were no complaints regarding the criteria that should be used as a basis for the evaluation of the offers.</seg>
<seg id="215">References to freelancers</seg>
<seg id="216">A small part of the service descriptions contained references to the freelancers involved.</seg>
<seg id="217">Some of their names were on the cover pages or in attached plans or reports.</seg>
<seg id="218">In one case, the contracting authority even explicitly asked applicants to contact the architect “on questions relating to the tender”.</seg>
<seg id="219">In the building construction sector in particular, the contracting authorities attributed the complaints shown mainly to the omissions of the freelancers commissioned to draw up the service specifications.</seg>
<seg id="220">The construction services pointed out the lack of capacity in order to be able to adequately control the specifications.</seg>
<seg id="221">NKÚ</seg>
<seg id="222">Technical specifications and product-neutral invitation to tender For the public contract for the construction of a residential building with 12 residential units, a supplier and a specific product brand were specified in the service description.</seg>
<seg id="223">The awarding authority did not allow the use of comparable products without giving reasons.</seg>
<seg id="224">When several university buildings were erected, suppliers and products were also specified in the tender.</seg>
<seg id="225">Service descriptions with service units</seg>
<seg id="226">In the case of construction projects in some industrial areas, the contracting authority did not clearly specify the scope and type of services required in the service descriptions.</seg>
<seg id="227">As performance units, it only stated the converted space of the individual buildings in cubic meters.</seg>
<seg id="228">Completeness of the service descriptions</seg>
<seg id="229">When building a bypass, the specifications were changed four times as part of a restricted procedure between August and September 2009,</seg>
<seg id="230">since the scope of services had increased significantly and the technical requirements had changed.</seg>
<seg id="231">Tender documents for social buildings included inaccurate location information, inadequate preliminary construction studies and incomplete construction drawings, which meant that additional services had to be commissioned.</seg>
<seg id="232">When building a large library building, the specifications for the interior did not contain any requirements regarding product quality.</seg>
<seg id="233">As a result of these missing requirements, some subcontractors installed overpriced and inappropriately high-quality equipment.</seg>
<seg id="234">Lots and eligibility criteria</seg>
<seg id="235">In the Czech Republic, the division of construction work into partial lots or the award of partial orders is not mandatory.</seg>
<seg id="236">An examination of the three major sections of the construction of a freeway ring showed that if selected parts were awarded in batches, savings of up to EUR 31.6 million at a total cost of EUR 620.3 million would have been possible.</seg>
<seg id="237">In the case of six different structures alone, which were the subject of a single order, a lottery contract could have saved 2.5 million euros (25%).</seg>
