<seg id="597">EU law and anti-corruption requirements</seg>
<seg id="598">The EU requirements provide for a multi-stage process:</seg>
<seg id="599">The suitability of the bidders must first be determined.</seg>
<seg id="600">Bidders must be economically and financially efficient and have the necessary professional and technical expertise.</seg>
<seg id="601">Companies are to be excluded from participation in the procurement procedure, which z. B. are legally convicted of bribery or fraud.</seg>
<seg id="602">The offers of the non-excluded bidders are to be checked mathematically, technically and economically and to be evaluated on the basis of the previously announced award criteria.</seg>
<seg id="603">The client has to determine the most economically advantageous offer. The client has to examine offers with unusually low prices in particular.</seg>
<seg id="604">The examination and evaluation of the offers is a particularly manipulation-prone phase of the award procedure.</seg>
<seg id="605">For example, bidders can be unjustifiably excluded or offers that do not meet the requirements can be left in competition.</seg>
<seg id="606">The preference or disadvantage of bidders can impermissibly affect the result of the evaluation and thus prevent the most economically advantageous offer from being determined.</seg>
<seg id="607">The awarding authority must therefore take special precautions to ensure that the persons responsible for the examination and assessment meet the requirements for integrity and specialist knowledge.</seg>
<seg id="608">It also has to ensure the transparency and traceability of the procedure and the decisions made.</seg>
<seg id="609">Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law</seg>
<seg id="610">Same or similar regulations</seg>
<seg id="611">In line with EU requirements, the offers in both countries are to be checked and evaluated in a multi-stage process.</seg>
<seg id="612">The requirements for the proof of suitability to be submitted by the companies as well as the award criteria to be taken into account in the evaluation and their weighting are specified in the notices or in the award documents and cannot be changed during the procedure.</seg>
<seg id="613">After checking the suitability of the bidder, the suitability criteria may no longer be used when evaluating the offers.</seg>
<seg id="614">The rating must be limited to the award criteria.</seg>
<seg id="615">The submitted offers must first be formally checked immediately to see whether they are complete and whether they contain e.g. B. abnormalities are included which could indicate possible intent to manipulate.</seg>
<seg id="616">If bidders are excluded from further review and evaluation of their offers, they must be informed immediately.</seg>
