<seg id="695">Summary findings</seg>
<seg id="696">The regulations for the examination and evaluation of the offers correspond to the requirements of the EU in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="697">Regarding the details of the procedure and the selection of the people involved, the respective regulations differ.</seg>
<seg id="698">In Germany, the process flow is regulated more strictly than in the Czech Republic by detailed requirements, in particular on the implementation of the multiple-eyes principle and to protect the offers.</seg>
<seg id="699">The same applies to the requirements on the basis of which the appropriateness of the prices offered must be checked.</seg>
<seg id="700">In both countries, it had to be ascertained in some of the award procedures that were examined that essential procedural steps in the examination and evaluation of the offers were not or only insufficiently documented.</seg>
<seg id="701">Without comprehensibility and transparency of the examination and evaluation decisions, possible manipulative interventions are favored.</seg>
<seg id="702">A particularly serious defect was the handover of all offers to third parties without the contracting authority having sufficiently looked through and documented the offers beforehand and thus protected them from possible manipulations in the further process.</seg>
<seg id="703">If contracting authorities have tasks in the examination and evaluation of the offers carried out by third parties, adequate precautions and an increased control effort are necessary to counter the increased risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="704">When examining the appropriateness of the prices, the audited departments in Germany did not always make full use of the specified instruments and did not adequately examine the price structure of the offers.</seg>
<seg id="705">In the Czech Republic, complaints arose primarily in the aptitude test and in the application of the evaluation criteria.</seg>
