<seg id="748">In both countries, deadlines for placing orders were exceeded.</seg>
<seg id="749">This can lead to economic disadvantages and increase the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="750">Building administrations should avoid the shortcomings highlighted when completing their procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="751">Documentation, reporting and reporting obligations</seg>
<seg id="752">The award procedures are to be documented comprehensibly during their individual stages with regard to the decisive findings as well as the reasons for the individual decisions.</seg>
<seg id="753">For EU-wide procedures, the orders placed must be made known.</seg>
<seg id="754">The order data are also recorded in EU statistics.</seg>
<seg id="755">Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption The documentation of the procurement procedures implements a fundamental requirement of the EU-wide transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="756">A carefully and promptly created documentation only makes it possible to understand the award decisions.</seg>
<seg id="757">In particular, it also serves to provide effective legal protection for bidders when awarding contracts above the EU thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="758">Proper documentation is also an essential part of preventing corruption, since the need to give detailed reasons for award decisions considerably limits the scope for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="759">The relevant contracting authority must notify the Office for Official Publications of the EU of the notice of an order placed in an EU-wide procurement procedure within 48 days.</seg>
<seg id="760">The Office publishes the notices in the Official Journal of the EU and thus also implements the transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="761">The contracting authorities must also collect the essential data of their procurement procedures and report them to the relevant national ministries of the EU Commission.</seg>
<seg id="762">On this basis, the EU Commission produces EU statistics every year, through which it can obtain an overview of the development of the internal market in construction services.</seg>
<seg id="763">Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law</seg>
<seg id="764">Same or similar regulations</seg>
<seg id="765">Both countries have fully implemented the EU legal requirements for documentation and reporting requirements into national law.</seg>
<seg id="766">The regulations on documentation and reporting for EU statistics are largely the same in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="767">Regulations that differ from each other</seg>
<seg id="768">In the Czech Republic, the obligation to publish contracts is not only restricted to EU-wide awards, but also extends to other award procedures.</seg>
<seg id="769">The notice period has been reduced to 15 days.</seg>
<seg id="770">In Germany, in addition to EU-wide awards, there is an obligation to publish only in the case of restricted invitations to tender and for direct awards from value limits of 25,000 euros or 15,000 euros without sales tax (so-called ex-post transparency).</seg>
<seg id="771">Below these value limits and in the case of public tenders, only the companies involved in the competition process receive information about the placing of orders.</seg>
<seg id="772">Essential test results</seg>
<seg id="773">BRH</seg>
<seg id="774">documentation</seg>
<seg id="775">A large number of the award procedures examined were not fully documented.</seg>
<seg id="776">The award notes did not contain all the necessary information, such as B. to justify product specifications or to refer to national regulations.</seg>
<seg id="777">In the case of a procurement procedure, the contracting authority did not justify why it placed the order with a company, even though the offer did not contain any evidence to be submitted.</seg>
<seg id="778">In a few cases, the documents from the contracting authorities did not contain all the evidence required to document the award procedure.</seg>
<seg id="779">Contract award notices</seg>
<seg id="780">In some EU-wide procurement procedures, the contracting authorities failed to make the award of the contract known.</seg>
<seg id="781">In further procurement procedures, there was no evidence that the contracting authorities had announced the orders placed.</seg>
<seg id="782">Reporting and reporting obligations</seg>
<seg id="783">The statistical statements viewed contained the required minimum information. They had been created and sent on time.</seg>
<seg id="784">Ex post transparency</seg>
<seg id="785">In most cases, the audited building authorities published the order data for the completed award procedures.</seg>
<seg id="786">In the case of a building administration, however, this data was not published due to a transmission error.</seg>
<seg id="787">The building authorities only noticed this error after half a year,</seg>
<seg id="788">so that the contract data for the award procedures that had been completed by then were not published.</seg>
<seg id="789">NKÚ</seg>
<seg id="790">documentation</seg>
<seg id="791">The documentation of the award procedure showed considerable shortcomings in the construction of a large sports event. This was mainly incorrect information, such as incorrect offer prices in the minutes of the evaluation committees.</seg>
<seg id="792">In addition, some minutes of the opening of offers were not signed.</seg>
<seg id="793">Contract award notices</seg>
<seg id="794">In several road construction projects, announcements about awarded contracts were only published late or not at all.</seg>
<seg id="795">Summary findings</seg>
<seg id="796">The regulations on documentation and on reporting and reporting obligations are largely the same in both countries and implement the EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="797">This generally guarantees the transparency of the award procedure, including the placing of orders.</seg>
<seg id="798">The regulations to be applied in the Czech Republic for publication go a little further than the requirements in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="799">The shortcomings in the documentation and in the announcements, which have been pointed out, in some cases significantly restricted the orripreventive effect of these instruments in the respective award procedure.</seg>
<seg id="800">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="801">Building administrations should further improve the transparency of their procurement procedures and contract awards and fully meet their reporting and reporting obligations.</seg>
<seg id="802">Summary evaluation and recommendations</seg>
<seg id="803">The parallel audits of the NKÚ and the BRH focused on two focal points that are essential in the Czech Republic and Germany for the awarding of construction works by public authorities: the application of the EU procurement regulations and the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="804">The requirements of EU law enable cross-border competition to create a European single market.</seg>
<seg id="805">Anti-corruption measures not only serve to prevent or at least reduce corruption. They are also intended to avert economic damage and a possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the state.</seg>
<seg id="806">The audit findings of the two courts of auditors regarding the application of the procurement law regulations in both countries and the comparison of these regulations reveal insights into similarities and differences that can be helpful for both countries in the further development of their procurement law and its application.</seg>
<seg id="807">Application of EU procurement rules</seg>
<seg id="808">Both countries have implemented the EU requirements for the awarding of construction works into national law.</seg>
<seg id="809">This gives the Czech Republic and Germany an important common basis for the awarding of construction services and taking into account the essential requirements of competition, equal treatment of the companies involved and the transparency of the award procedures.</seg>
<seg id="810">The building authorities of both countries have partially enforced these bids very extensively through further administrative regulations.</seg>
<seg id="811">The Czech Republic has largely transferred the requirements for construction work to be awarded across the EU to its nationally adjustable procurement procedures below the EU threshold.</seg>
<seg id="812">However, the studies carried out by the audit offices have shown that the building authorities have not fully complied with the requirements of EU law in all areas.</seg>
<seg id="813">The building authorities in Germany should further improve the quality of their procurement procedures in order to be able to eliminate the above-mentioned complaints when implementing the EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="814">The audits in the Czech Republic have primarily identified dangers that affect the profitability of the award.</seg>
<seg id="815">Incomplete service descriptions made additional services necessary, which were often awarded in violation of legal regulations. In addition, the cost calculations were mostly inadequate. Excessive qualification requirements also reduced the number of possible bidders and restricted competition, particularly in the traffic structures.</seg>
<seg id="816">Corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="817">The purpose of the investigations was not to uncover cases of corruption,</seg>
<seg id="818">also because the audit offices do not have the appropriate instruments for this.</seg>
<seg id="819">However, the audit offices can check to what extent the administrations of both countries have taken measures against corruption and manipulation when awarding construction services and how these requirements are applied.</seg>
<seg id="820">Both countries have different priorities when it comes to preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="821">Above all, the German regulations provide for largely unrestricted competition as well as transparency and controls as central elements in the prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="822">The Czech regulations are primarily aimed at increasing the transparency of the procedures.</seg>
<seg id="823">BRH</seg>
<seg id="824">In Germany, general principles of corruption prevention apply, which the entire federal administration must apply.</seg>
<seg id="825">These principles are also implemented in the specifications for the awarding of construction services and geared to their specific requirements.</seg>
<seg id="826">The corresponding regulations partly specify very precisely how the anti-corruption bids are to be taken into account when the award procedure is carried out and when selecting the people involved.</seg>
<seg id="827">According to the BRH, the priority of the principle of the open procedure or the public tender is a suitable instrument in order to be able to significantly reduce the risk of corruption when awarding construction works. However, restrictions on competition increase the risk of manipulative interventions.</seg>
<seg id="828">Risk analyzes and adequate controls (especially the multiple-eyes principle), the requirements for transparency and documentation of the award procedure as well as various organizational measures are also effective measures to prevent corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="829">The BRH therefore sees no fundamental need to change the corresponding requirements of the administrations when awarding construction services.</seg>
<seg id="830">The rules for preventing corruption are largely taken into account in practice.</seg>
<seg id="831">The shortcomings identified in some areas have shown deficiencies in the implementation of some requirements.</seg>
<seg id="832">The building authorities should train their employees further on the requirements for preventing corruption and raise their awareness of this problem even more.</seg>
<seg id="833">A significant part of the complaints related to tasks that the building authorities had delegated to freelancers.</seg>
<seg id="834">Without controls and adequate safeguards, the risk of abuse increases when delegating tasks.</seg>
<seg id="835">Manipulation and corruption-prone tasks should therefore only be delegated to third parties if the administration can guarantee a sufficient level of protection against unauthorized interference.</seg>
<seg id="836">NKÚ</seg>
<seg id="837">The Czech Republic adopted an anti-corruption strategy at government level, in which the area of ​​public procurement is the main component.</seg>
<seg id="838">The public procurement law and the associated implementing provisions have been significantly changed.</seg>
<seg id="839">The NKÚ audits took place during the implementation of this strategy.</seg>
<seg id="840">The strategy adopted and the new legal provisions are likely to be effective improvement measures, since the awarding authorities justify the cost-effectiveness of the placing of orders, the calculation of the expected prices, the appropriateness of the qualification requirements, the essential evaluation criteria and the type of evaluations, and properly document and publish all these aspects have to.</seg>
<seg id="841">recommendations</seg>
<seg id="842">The NKÚ and the BRH are generally positive about the implementation of the EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="843">The widespread acceptance in practice has confirmed that the EU's requirements of competition, equal treatment and transparency are a suitable basis for the awarding of construction works within the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="844">The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also serve as the basis for similar projects that enable and promote cross-border competition.</seg>
<seg id="845">In view of the enormous material and non-material damage potential from manipulation and corruption in the awarding of construction services, both audit offices see the building authorities in their countries required to continue their measures against corruption and manipulation and, if necessary, to improve them.</seg>
<seg id="846">In particular, the organization and procedures of the award procedure should be continuously examined for weaknesses and risks in order to identify the need for action and to be able to initiate suitable countermeasures.</seg>
<seg id="847">A comparison of public procurement practices in both countries suggests that the proportion of open cases in the Czech Republic should be increased, as open ones offer more scope for competition and can significantly reduce the risk of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="848">A greater division of construction services into lots can also have a favorable effect on the offer prices, provided that this results in greater competition with a higher number of bidders.</seg>
<seg id="849">Ensuring the correct implementation of the procurement procedures is an essential basis for efficient public contracting.</seg>
<seg id="850">In Germany, the tendering procedures are carried out by the specialized building authorities. In the Czech Republic, however, these tasks - with the exception of transport construction projects - are carried out by the ministries themselves or contractors commissioned by them.</seg>
<seg id="851">The audit offices of both countries are concerned to continue developing the knowledge that is important to them after the completion of their joint project and, if necessary, to present it to the parliament and government of their country.</seg>
<seg id="852">Both SAIs are also convinced that the principles of public procurement law set out in this report and their implementation are also of international interest to the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI). Because the principles and knowledge presented are of general importance in order to counter corruption effectively and to ensure the economic awarding of construction works in a well-functioning and fair competition.</seg>
<seg id="853">Investments</seg>
