<p>
<seg id="1">Management of sales tax in the Czech Republic and in the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Control test report</seg>
<seg id="3">Foreword</seg>
<seg id="4">Taxes are the main source of income for public budgets.</seg>
<seg id="5">A focus of the work of the Court of Auditors should therefore be on the audit of this area.</seg>
<seg id="6">This applies in particular to VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="7">This alone causes an estimated 100 billion euros in tax losses per year in the European Union1.</seg>
<seg id="8">Already with the VI. EUROSAI Congress 2005 in Bonn informed the participants of the need for closer cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="9">This enables the audit offices e.g. Exchange examination approaches and optimize examination practice.</seg>
<seg id="10">Value added tax (VAT) is particularly suitable for cooperation because it is harmonized within the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="11">In 2006, the auditors of both countries audited for the first time in parallel in the area of ​​VAT.</seg>
<seg id="12">The corresponding audit report was published in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="13">As VAT fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, close cooperation between the Court of Auditors is required. This enables a comprehensive assessment to be made as to whether the measures taken are suitable for effectively countering VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="14">The two SAIs decided to continue their cooperation and carried out a second parallel audit. Management of sales tax in the Czech Republic and in the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="15">1 Introduction</seg>
<seg id="16">Exam number: (CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892</seg>
<seg id="17">Subject of the audit: (CZ) Administration of VAT (D) Bilateral audit with the Court of Audit of the Czech Republic (hereinafter NKÚ), control audit</seg>
<seg id="18">Exam objective:</seg>
<seg id="19">(CZ) The VAT administration and the treatment of selected sales between entrepreneurs from the Czech Republic (hereinafter CZ) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter Germany) should be examined. In addition, the procedures used by the tax authorities for intergovernmental assistance should be examined.</seg>
<seg id="20">(D) The audit was intended to evaluate how the financial administration implemented the recommendations made by the Court of Auditors.</seg>
<seg id="21">In addition, other test fields linked to the VAT should be worked on.</seg>
<seg id="22">The findings made here should be compared to determine whether the taxation process can be optimized.</seg>
<seg id="23">The examination period was the years 2006 to 2008 including relevant information from the period before the examination period until the end of the examination.</seg>
<seg id="24">2. Summary of results and evaluation of the parallel test</seg>
<seg id="25">The audit offices of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have agreed to carry out an audit to manage VAT.</seg>
<seg id="26">In the previous parallel review, they uncovered suspected intra-community sales,</seg>
<seg id="27">which made a further examination expedient.</seg>
<seg id="28">Based on the audit findings, the two audit offices made recommendations on how to manage VAT.</seg>
<seg id="29">The aim of the control test was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented. In addition, the suspected cases identified should be investigated.</seg>
<seg id="30">The examination also dealt with other issues. This included selected cases of high-risk intra-Community sales, mutual administrative assistance in the recovery of VAT claims and the VAT check for large companies.</seg>
<seg id="31">The Court of Auditors found:</seg>
<seg id="32">1. Recommendations made on the basis of the previous test</seg>
<seg id="33">• Recommendation 1: The regulations for the registration of taxpayers should be harmonized within the EU</seg>
<seg id="34">At the first audit, the SAIs compared VAT registration procedures in the two countries and identified differences that caused problems.</seg>
<seg id="35">The Court of Auditors therefore recommended harmonizing taxpayer registration within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="36">This has also been taken up at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="37">The draft amendment to Council Regulation No. 1798/2003 provides for the current databases in the EU to be expanded, including a database with the identification number of VAT payers.</seg>
<seg id="38">The draft also provided for common rules for the registration of taxpayers and their deletion.</seg>
<seg id="39">The Court of Auditors expected Member States to agree on appropriate rules, in line with their fundamental decision, to remove unreliable entrepreneurs from the VAT system as early as possible.</seg>
<seg id="40">The Member States reached political agreement in ECOFIN on the latest version of the draft.</seg>
<seg id="41">The common regulations mentioned are no longer included. The two Court of Auditors regret that.</seg>
<seg id="42">They still consider such regulations to be important in order to prevent VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="43">• Recommendation 2: monthly submission of the summary reports. As a result of the first audit, the Court of Auditors recommended that the Member States should submit the summary reports (ZM) monthly in future.</seg>
<seg id="44">The amounts of intra-Community sales could then be checked sooner.</seg>
<seg id="45">Council Directive 2008/117 / EC amending Directive 2006/112 / EC on the common system of value added tax for the purpose of combating tax fraud in intra-Community transactions has shortened the period for the submission of the tax to one month.</seg>
<seg id="46">In the CZ, this requirement was implemented by an amendment to the VAT Act that came into force on January 1, 2010.</seg>
<seg id="47">In Germany, implementation only came into force on July 1, 2010. It has therefore not transposed the obligation to submit the ZM into national law on time.</seg>
<seg id="48">• Recommendation 3: Data comparison of VAT pre-registrations and the ZM in Germany for more reliable MIAS data and suggestion to check the merging of the procedures for VAT pre-registrations and ZM. The German tax authorities took up the recommendation made by the Federal Audit Office and set up a working group that should work out possible solutions.</seg>
<seg id="49">The work is still ongoing.</seg>
<seg id="50">The Federal Audit Office will monitor further developments.</seg>
<seg id="51">• Recommendation 4: exchange about successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level. In the course of the first audit, the two Court of Auditors agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by one Member State alone.</seg>
<seg id="52">Successful criteria as well as elements or approaches of a risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in every EU member state.</seg>
<seg id="53">If this does not happen, fraudsters will focus on the Member State with the weakest risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="54">The Court of Auditors found that the two Member States have different risk management systems that have both strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="55">The NKU examined the system of information exchange within the EU - EUROCANET, while the Federal Audit Office concentrated on Germany's participation in the "Platform for Risk Management".</seg>
<seg id="56">2. Control check of selected intra-community sales</seg>
<seg id="57">The auditors jointly examined sales at the first check, where it was doubtful whether they had actually been carried out or which had been declared differently by the taxpayers of the two states in the advance VAT returns (or VAT returns) or ZM.</seg>
<seg id="58">The audit offices selected nine cases of intra-Community deliveries of goods between the CZ and Germany for the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="59">The audits by the tax offices (FÄ) of both countries were not yet over when the first parallel audit was completed.</seg>
<seg id="60">The control audit has shown that the tax procedures for these selected sales have now been completed. The respective financial authorities had taken appropriate measures to do this (including the subsequent determination of VAT or the prevention of input tax refunds).</seg>
<seg id="61">3. Examination of selected, particularly risky intra-Community sales</seg>
<seg id="62">The audit also included highly risky intra-Community sales between taxpayers in the EU, which were recorded in the EUROCANET system.</seg>
<seg id="63">EUROCANET is used to identify risky taxpayers.</seg>
<seg id="64">Member States can participate in this system on a voluntary basis.</seg>
<seg id="65">The CZ is an active participant in EUROCANET. Germany has a passive status, i.e. H. it does not participate in data exchange within the framework of EUROCANET.</seg>
<seg id="66">From the perspective of an active participating State, it is unsatisfactory that other Member States refuse to participate actively.</seg>
<seg id="67">As a result, no information could be obtained about which suppliers with a German VAT ID would have been classified as high-risk cases.</seg>
<seg id="68">The NKU provided both normal transactions and suspected VAT fraud in the selected sales, among other things. a. Carousel fraud, tight.</seg>
<seg id="69">The FÄ could only check sales with high risk to a limited extent. This was particularly the case with so-called "missing traders", whereby an examination of the documents alone is hardly sufficient to prove fraud to the taxpayer.</seg>
<seg id="70">If carousel fraud is suspected for imports and exports</seg>
<seg id="71">it is recommended that the customs and tax authorities work more closely together in order to be able to track the identity of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the end customer.</seg>
<seg id="72">Germany and a number of other countries have declined to actively participate in EUROCANET because they do not believe there is a sufficient legal basis.</seg>
<seg id="73">The Federal Audit Office found that the German tax authorities use other tools to identify risky taxpayers.</seg>
<seg id="74">Nevertheless, there is a need for communication and exchange of experience between all EU member states.</seg>
<seg id="75">The Council of the EU agreed on a draft regulation</seg>
<seg id="76">was created by the EUROFISC.</seg>
<seg id="77">The experience gained so far with EUROCANET should flow into the planned network to combat VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="78">4. Mutual administrative assistance in the recovery of claims</seg>
<seg id="79">Intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims is subject to the same European legislation in all Member States.</seg>
<seg id="80">Therefore requests for intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims in the CZ and Germany are processed in the same way.</seg>
<seg id="81">The Federal Audit Office and the NKU compared the statistics that both Member States submitted to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.</seg>
<seg id="82">There were discrepancies in these statistics.</seg>
<seg id="83">The two Court of Auditors consider a renewed discussion of the statistics at EU level to be useful in order to avoid inconsistencies that still exist in the future.</seg>
<seg id="84">If this does not happen, the statistics cannot be used appropriately for comparisons.</seg>
<seg id="85">In addition, the statistics should include more information on VAT.</seg>
<seg id="86">An analysis of detailed data can make it easier for the Commission to support Member States in their efforts to combat VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="87">Both Court of Auditors believe that Member States with a low recovery rate should strive to at least match the average recovery rate.</seg>
<seg id="88">The Commission should assist Member States in this if so desired.</seg>
<seg id="89">5. VAT check for large companies</seg>
<seg id="90">The Court of Auditors analyzed the legal situation regarding the VAT check for large companies in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="91">In addition, they collected information from the financial authorities that they considered important in this context using a questionnaire.</seg>
<seg id="92">It became clear that the situation is different in the two countries.</seg>
<seg id="93">The CZ has a system for the selection of risky cases that includes a large amount of relevant data (including information on VAT audits, data from balance sheets and profit and loss accounts).</seg>
<seg id="94">The overall VAT control can thus be effectively controlled and analyzed.</seg>
<seg id="95">A special tax office for large companies is to be set up in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="96">There is still no comparable system in Germany. This makes it more difficult to control and analyze the overall VAT control.</seg>
<seg id="97">The German financial administration focuses more on the selection of relevant individual cases and relies in particular on data from the advance VAT returns or VAT returns and the ZM.</seg>
<seg id="98">Various risk management components that still need to be improved support the evaluation of this data.</seg>
<seg id="99">3. Examination procedure</seg>
<seg id="100">3.1 Examination procedure in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="101">Department II - State Budgetary Income and the regional departments IX Pilsen, X České Budějovice, XIII Brno and XV Ostrava carried out audits from May 2009 to February 2010.</seg>
<seg id="102">The audited bodies were the Czech Ministry of Finance and 25 FÄ: tax office (FA) Brno II, FA Brno III, FA Brno IV, FA in Břeclav, FA in Domažlice, FA in Hodonín, FA in Hradec Králové, FA in Cheb, FA in Jablonec nad Nisou, FA in Karlovy Vary, FA in Kralupy nad Vltavou, FA in Kraslice, FA Ostrava I, FA Ostrava III, FA in Písek, FA in Pilsen, FA Prague 1, FA Prague 4, FA Prague 8, FA in Rakovník, FA in Sokolov, FA in Tábor, FA in Vysoké Mýto, FA in Zlín and FA in Žamberk.</seg>
<seg id="103">The Senate of the Czech Court of Auditors approved the audit findings on April 27, 2010.</seg>
<seg id="104">3.2 Examination procedure in Germany</seg>
<seg id="105">The traffic tax audit area and employees of the assigned PÄB Berlin, Frankfurt / Main and Munich audited from February 2009 to February 2010.</seg>
<seg id="106">After selecting the sample cases, they announced the exam in several countries:</seg>
<seg id="107">• Bavaria, • Hamburg, • Hesse, • North Rhine-Westphalia, • Saxony. In addition, they conducted interviews in the Federal Ministry of Finance (Federal Ministry of Finance).</seg>
<seg id="108">Tax files from the following FÄ were included in the audit: • Erlangen, Central Tax Office Munich, Hof, Schwandorf, Regensburg, Weiden in der Oberpfalz, Grafenau; • Hamburg-Nord, Hamburg-Hansa, special tax office Hamburg for large companies; • Wiesbaden I, Wiesbaden II, Darmstadt; • Essen-NordOst, FA Essen for tax audits at large companies and corporations, Lüdenscheid; • Chemnitz-Süd.</seg>
<seg id="109">In addition, discussions were held with the FÄ Mühlacker, Reutlingen, Starnberg, Verden, Erfurt, Leipzig, Halle-Süd and the OFD Frankfurt / Main, Chemnitz and Münster.</seg>
<seg id="110">The Federal Audit Office informed the Federal Ministry of Finance of the audit results in April 2010.</seg>
<seg id="111">3.3 Cooperation between the two audit offices</seg>
<seg id="112">In advance of the parallel audit, representatives of both audit offices met in September 2008 to discuss and determine the audit topics.</seg>
<seg id="113">In December 2008, the Presidents of both Court of Auditors signed an agreement to cooperate on the parallel audit.</seg>
<seg id="114">At a meeting in Bonn in June 2009, the examination teams briefed themselves on the initial results obtained during the examination preparation, discussed possible examination approaches and agreed on how to proceed.</seg>
<seg id="115">A second meeting took place in Prague from December 2-4, 2009.</seg>
<seg id="116">The examination teams exchanged the examination results gained up to that point and agreed the schedule for the preparation of the joint examination report.</seg>
<seg id="117">The two Court of Auditors identified the following issues for their parallel review: • Evaluation of the recommendations given in the previous report; • Review of selected cases of intra-Community sales between taxpayers from the CZ and Germany that could not be fully resolved during the first parallel review; • Review of selected intra-Community sales classified as risky between taxpayers from the CZ and Germany; • Examine the procedures of the two tax administrations with regard to intergovernmental administrative assistance in the recovery of VAT claims; • VAT audits at large companies.</seg>
<seg id="118">The report on the results of the parallel review was prepared during a working meeting in June 2010.</seg>
<seg id="119">4. Audit the administration of sales tax in selected areas</seg>
<seg id="120">4.1 Implementation of the recommendations from the first joint examination</seg>
<seg id="121">4.1.1 Implementation of the recommendations in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="122">Recommendation 1</seg>
<seg id="123">Harmonization of requirements for registration of taxpayers within the EU</seg>
<seg id="124">on the results of the first audit, the Czech Court of Auditors recommended that the requirements for VAT registration be amended and new rules for deleting the registration in the CZ introduced.</seg>
<seg id="125">These changed rules should more effectively contain the risk of possible tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="126">In certain cases, it was found that the FÄ did not delete the VAT registration of taxpayers if they did not fulfill their obligations under Czech Law No. 235/2004 (hereinafter referred to as "VAT Law").</seg>
<seg id="127">So far, the Czech Ministry of Finance has not submitted an amendment to oblige the FÄ to delete if taxpayers repeatedly fail to submit VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="128">In accordance with Czech VAT law, the FA may delete a taxpayer's registration ex officio if a) the taxpayer has not made any sales for twelve consecutive months and has not informed the FA of the reasons therefor; b) the taxpayer has not fulfilled his obligations under the VAT Act; c) the taxpayer no longer meets the requirements for tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="129">The first examination had shown that, due to the existing legal situation, the FA Prague 1 had to delete the VAT registration of “foreign taxpayers” 3 with effect from January 31 of the following calendar year if they were not obliged to register and pay VAT in the current calendar year .</seg>
