<seg id="617">5. Conclusions</seg>
<seg id="618">The cooperation between the two audit offices has proven itself.</seg>
<seg id="619">In this way, necessary knowledge about the systems used in both countries could be obtained: This applies in particular to: • Intra-Community sales, • Risk management at VAT, particularly with regard to the selection of risky sales, • Collection of VAT claims and • VAT audits of large companies.</seg>
<seg id="620">The audit revealed differences in strategies to detect VAT fraud and in the systems discussed above.</seg>
<seg id="621">These findings can be used to improve existing processes.</seg>
<seg id="622">They can also be used to initiate a discussion with the interested parties as to which audit approaches and strategies can be used to combat fraud. This applies e.g. B. for the relationship within and between the Member States and the EU Commission.</seg>
<seg id="623">The experience and knowledge gained should encourage future audits of the administration of VAT together.</seg>
